<TITLE>Hongkongers could face damp night as rain forecast for Year of Rooster fireworks show</TITLE>
<TEXT>
Hongkongers are being warned they could face rain tonight as they watch almost 24 000 firework shells explode over Victoria Harbour on Sunday to mark the Year of the Rooster Crowds are expected to gather in Tsim Sha Tsui Mid levels Central Wan Chai Causeway Bay and Hung Hom bypass to watch the annual Lunar New Year display which will this year consist of eight scenes lasting 23 minutes in total Year of Rooster bright for Hong Kong if city unites Lunar New Year temple ritual reveals The Hong Kong Observatory said visitors could endure drizzly spells in the evening although it should remain relatively warm at about 20 degrees Celsius A spokesman for the city s official weather forecaster said cloudy periods could also limit visibility in some areas Watch Hong Kong welcomes 2017 as fireworks light up Victoria Harbour It will be mainly cloudy with one or two light rain patches he said Visibility will be relatively low in some areas There will be sunny intervals in the afternoon and moderate to fresh easterly winds occasionally strong offshore and on high ground at first In the ambitious pyrotechnic display 23 888 firework shells are to be deployed over the harbour from three barges The display which will be broadcast live on the Post s Facebook page is estimated to cost HK 8 million The production is sponsored by Unique Timepieces by Halewinner a luxury watch company chaired by Karson Choi Ka tsan a son of billionaire toy maker Francis Choi The display s first scene is to feature a time tunnel image incorporating the pattern of the figure 20 to mark the 20th anniversary of Hong Kong s establishment as a special administrative region of China a Halewinner spokesman said Watch January 29 fireworks preview embedded content The festive auspicious sign of the figure 8 which in Chinese rhymes with the character for prosperity and a Chinese character for auspiciousness are to be shown in scenes two and four Other major fireworks displays in Hong Kong take place on July 1 this year to celebrate the 20th anniversary of the city s handover from UK to Chinese authorities and October 1 for National Day Another event is held on December 31 The Lunar New Year show comes a day after the city s annual parade through Tsim Sha Tsui Thousands of people lined the streets on Saturday night to watch nearly 3 000 performers from some 25 international and local performing groups 
